t up by the roadside or in a marketplace, from Middle English <i>cros</i> (Old English <i>cros</i> and Old Norse <i>kross</i>, ultimately from Latin <i>crux</i>, <i>crucem</i>). It is commonly Latinized in medieval records as <i>ad crucem</i> and <i>de Cruce</i> but examples of this can just as well belong to the synonymous but less common name   Crouch  . In a few cases the surname may have been given originally to someone who lived by a crossroads, but this sense of the word seems to have been a comparatively late development. In other cases, the surname (and its European cognates; see 3 below) may have denoted someone who carried the cross in processions of the Christian Church, but in English at least the usual word for this sense was   Crozier  .","Irish: shortened form of   McCrossen  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning вҖҳcrossвҖҷ or вҖҳthe crossвҖҷ, such as French   Lacroix  , German   Kreutz  , and Slovenian and Croatian <b>KriЕҫ</b> (see   Kriz  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Crouch","meanings":["English (southeastern): from Middle English <i>crouch(e)</i>, <i>cruch(e)</i> вҖҳcrossвҖҷ (Old English <i>crЕ«c</i>, ultimately from Latin <i>crux</i>, <i>crucem</i>; the Old English <i>crЕ«c</i> was replaced in Middle English by the word <i>cross</i>, from Old Norse <i>kross</i>), applied as a topographic name for someone who lived by a cross."]},{"name":"Croce","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Angelo, Carlo, Nicola, Salvatore, Vito, Antonio, Gino, Rocco, Saverio, Amadeo, Amerigo.","Italian:","from <i>croce</i> вҖҳcrossвҖҷ (from Latin <i>crux</i>, genitive <i>crucis</i>), applied as a topographic name for someone who lived by a roadside cross, or a nickname for someone who carried the cross in religious processions. Compare English   Cross  ."]},{"name":"Grose","meanings":["Cornish: topographic name for someone who lived near a stone cross set up by the roadside or in a marketplace, Cornish <i>crous</i> (from Latin <i>crux</i>, <i>crucis</i>). Compare   Cross  .","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Crosse","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cross  ."]},{"name":"Kreutz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Gottfried, Orlo, Reinhold.","German: topographic name for someone who lived near a cross set up by the roadside, in a marketplace, or as a field or boundary marker, from Middle High German <i>kriuz(e)</i> вҖҳcrossвҖҷ. Compare   Cross  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names В© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394вҖ“1437 ; ruled  1424вҖ“37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566вҖ“1625 ; reigned  1567вҖ“1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633вҖ“1701 ; reigned  1685вҖ“8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (вҖҳBonnie Prince CharlieвҖҷ) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":25,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":34,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":45,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":47,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":61,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":63,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"James Cross was born in 1524, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England as the son of Anne Keynes. He married Lady Margery Rotsey in 1544, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1604, in Wotton under Edge, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 80, and was buried in Wotton under Edge, Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"1524вҖ“1604":"1524вҖ“1604","1519вҖ“1558":"1519вҖ“1558","1548вҖ“1647":"1548вҖ“1647","1500вҖ“Female":"1500вҖ“Surnud","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","24 November 1558":"24. november 1558","1519":"1519","1604":"1604","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","1647":"1647","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Elmore, Gloucestershire, England":"Elmore, Gloucestershire, England","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Synwell, Wotton-under-Edge, Stroud district, Gloucestershire, England":"Wotton under Edge, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1524вҖ“1604":"1524вҖ“1604","1519вҖ“1558":"1519вҖ“1558","1548вҖ“1647":"1548вҖ“1647","1500вҖ“Female":"1500вҖ“Kuollut","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","24 November 1558":"24. marraskuuta 1558","1519":"1519","1604":"1604","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","1647":"1647","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Elmore, Gloucestershire, England":"Elmore, Gloucestershire, England","Northampton,